Do you prefer to save money or spend money?

I would say I try to strike a balance between saving and spending money. On the one hand, I do enjoy treating myself occasionally, whether it’s buying something I like or going out with friends. However, I tend to lean more towards saving because I think it’s important to be financially prepared for the future.

For example, I always try to set aside a portion of my income each month for emergencies or long-term goals. At the same time, I believe it’s equally important to enjoy the present, so I don’t deprive myself completely. Overall, I’d say I’m quite careful with money, but I still allow myself some flexibility.

How do you save money?
I usually save a portion of my income each month. In addition, I make a consicious effort to avoid impulse purchases, and I tend to cook at home rather than eat out frequently, which helps me cut down on unnecessary expenses.

What do you think about payment apps or mobile payments?
I think they’re brilliant, to be honest. They’re incredibly convenient and much quicker than dealing with cash or even cards. I also like the fact that you can easily track your spending through the app, which makes it easier to manage your finances. On top of that, many payment apps are quite secure, so I feel comfortable using them on a daily basis.

Do you use a credit card to buy things?
Not really at the moment. I'm quite cautious when it comes to credit cards because I don't want to get into debt or develop bad spending habits. I prefer to stick to my debit card, so I'm only using money that I actually have, which helps me stay on top of my spending and live within my means. I feel like it gives me better control over my finances, and I don't have to worry about paying anything back later.

Do you think cash will still be popular in the future?
It’s quite difficult to predict, to be honest. Cash is clearly becoming less common, especially with the growing popularity of contactless and mobile payments. However, I don’t think it will disappear completely. There will likely always be a place for physical money, particularly among older generations or in informal settings like local markets or car boot sales.

In addition, some people still prefer using cash because it gives them a better sense of control over their spending. So while its usage may decline, I believe cash will continue to exist alongside digital payment methods for the foreseeable future.

Do you generally spend a lot of money?
I try to be quite mindful of my spending habits. I don’t like wasting money on unnecessary things, but I do enjoy treating myself from time to time, especially when I go out with friends on weekends. Overall, I’d say I strike a balance between being careful with money and still enjoying life.

Do your parents give you pocket money to help with the housework?
I used to get pocket money for doing chores around the house when I was younger. However, now that I have a job, I don’t rely on it anymore. That said, I still help out at home because I think it’s important to share responsibilities and support my family, rather than doing it for money.

Do people in your country give money as a gift to children?
Definitely. It’s quite common for children to receive money as a gift, especially on occasions like birthdays or Christmas. Many relatives prefer giving cash because it allows children to choose what they really want, rather than receiving something they might not use.

It also encourages them to start saving from a young age, as they can put the money aside for something special instead of spending it straight away.
